{
  "final_answer": "## Consolidated Capex as a Multiple of Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA\n\n### Calculation\n\n| Metric | FY2025 ($M) |\n|--------|------------|\n| Consolidated Capital Expenditures | $20,737 |\n| Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA | $7,168 |\n| **Capex / Connectivity Adj. EBITDA** | **2.89×** |\n\n$$\\frac{\\$20{,}737M}{\\$7{,}168M} = 2.89\\times$$\n\n### What This Implies About the Structural Role of IPO Capital vs. Internally Generated Cash\n\n**1. Internally generated cash falls far short of capital requirements.**\n\nThe 2.89× multiple means that even the company's single strongest cash-generating segment—Connectivity (Starlink), which produced $7,168M in Adjusted EBITDA—would need to dedicate nearly three full years of its entire EBITDA output just to fund one year of consolidated capex. Put differently, Connectivity Adjusted EBITDA covers only ~34.6% of total capex in a single year.\n\nThe picture is even more constrained at the consolidated level:\n\n| Metric | FY2025 ($M) |\n|--------|------------|\n| Total Consolidated Adjusted EBITDA | $6,584 |\n| Cash Flow from Operations | $6,785 |\n| Consolidated Capex | $20,737 |\n| **Implied Free Cash Flow** | **$(13,952)** |\n\nTotal consolidated Adjusted EBITDA ($6,584M) is actually *less* than Connectivity Adjusted EBITDA alone, because the AI segment is burning $(1,237M) in negative Adjusted EBITDA and Space contributes only $653M. Operating cash flow of $6,785M covers just 32.7% of capex, leaving a ~$14 billion annual funding gap.\n\n**2. IPO capital is structurally essential, not supplemental.**\n\nThe capex burden is driven overwhelmingly by the AI segment ($12,727M, or 61.4% of total capex in FY2025), which is loss-making and cannot self-fund. Connectivity's robust EBITDA generation, while impressive, is consumed by its own segment capex ($4,178M) and cannot cross-subsidize the AI buildout at scale. This creates a structural dependency on external capital:\n\n- **The $20 billion SpaceX Bridge Loan** exists precisely to bridge this gap and explicitly requires repayment from IPO proceeds.\n- **The $1.5 billion revolving credit facility** provides additional liquidity headroom.\n- **Cash balances grew from $11.5B to $25.1B during FY2025**—not from operating surplus, but from financing inflows that massively exceeded the FCF deficit.\n\n**3. The IPO is a balance-sheet recapitalization, not a growth kicker.**\n\nBecause internally generated cash covers only ~one-third of annual capex, the IPO proceeds serve a fundamentally structural purpose: they convert what would be an unsustainable burn rate into a fundable investment program. Without external equity capital, the company would need to either (a) take on significantly more leverage beyond the already $29.1B in long-term debt as of Q1 2026, or (b) materially curtail capex in one or more segments.\n\nIn sum, the 2.89× ratio reveals that SpaceX's capital-intensive, multi-segment growth strategy (particularly the AI infrastructure buildout) is architecturally dependent on external capital markets. IPO proceeds are not a luxury or a war chest—they are a prerequisite for sustaining the company's disclosed investment trajectory. Connectivity Adjusted EBITDA is the company's cash engine, but it alone cannot power the full machine.\n\n---\n\n**Sources:**\n- SpaceX S-1 Filing (May 20, 2026): https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\n  - MD&A: Consolidated and segment capex, Segment Adjusted EBITDA reconciliation\n  - Consolidated Statements of Cash Flows: Operating cash flow, investing activities, ending cash balances\n  - Use of Proceeds section; Liquidity and Capital Resources discussion",
